Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B ,
Happy Wednesday! We=E2=80=99re coming to you mid-week this week because we =
wanted to time today=E2=80=99s essay with the Series A announcement of a No=
t Boring Capital Fund III portfolio company we=E2=80=99re really excited ab=
out: Atomic AI [ https://substack.com/redirect/aea53e1a-9e64-48c9-a16c-9956=
8f74fde1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ].
Atomic AI is a perfect example of the kind of company we want to invest in =
at Not Boring Capital. It=E2=80=99s built on cutting edge science at the in=
tersection of Bits and Atoms, has a path to becoming a $10B+ company, and a=
s importantly, will bend the world=E2=80=99s trajectory upwards if it succe=
eds. Specifically, by unlocking the structure of RNA, Atomic AI could unloc=
k the potential of RNA-targeting and RNA-based medicines, help cure previou=
sly incurable diseases, and save millions of lives.
Today=E2=80=99s piece is a collaboration between me and Elliot Hershberg [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/6941be9a-c83e-44af-b6b0-6531f301a96b?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], our Biotech P=
artner and author of the excellent The Century of Biology . Simply put, we =
wouldn=E2=80=99t have been able to invest in Atomic AI without Elliot, and =
the company fits his Sequencing, Synthesis, Software, and Scale as well as =
a small molecule drug can now fit an RNA target (don't worry, we'll explain=
). His knowledge of the science at play littttle bit stronger than mine, an=
d the only way to properly tell Atomic AI=E2=80=99s story is by explaining =
both the cutting edge science and the powerful business model.=20
While ChatGPT is getting all of the attention, AI=E2=80=99s biggest breakth=
roughs so far have come from helping us better understand the human body at=
 the atomic level. Atomic AI is the latest breakthrough in using Bits to un=
derstand and influence Atoms.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it. =20
Atomic AI: Unlocking RNA [ https://substack.com/redirect/1638f2a9-e8be-4001=
-9f41-4e85c5f14faa?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ]
(Click =F0=9F=91=86to read the full piece online)
One view of recent history is that we=E2=80=99ve been in a Great Stagnation=
 since 1971. Starting with the Industrial Revolution and ending in that not=
orious year [ https://substack.com/redirect/a1d6658f-3883-4cc4-89df-3bd46f6=
275fe?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ],=
 humans made dizzying advances in our ability to shape Atoms into ever more=
 powerful configurations. Then, quite abruptly, we stopped. Or rather, we s=
hifted our innovative efforts to the world of Bits. To many, this signaled =
the end of real progress. The internet is useful, but Where is My Flying Ca=
r?=C2=A0
Now, with the dramatic rise of companies like Tesla, SpaceX, Anduril, and M=
oderna, this line of thinking goes, we may finally be shifting our efforts =
back to where they should have been all along: the physical world.=C2=A0
This binary battle between Bits and Atoms is not how we view the world at N=
ot Boring. We=E2=80=99d bet that if you zoom out, this Bits-focused interlu=
de will be an Archimedes lever for the progress made in the decades and cen=
turies to come. It=E2=80=99s not Bits versus Atoms. The most impactful prog=
ress will come at the intersection of Bits and Atoms.=C2=A0
Atomic AI is a perfect case study. Atoms and Bits are right there in the na=
me.=C2=A0
