Chapter 1: Structure and Function
DNA=E2=80=99s double helical structure is one of the most iconic and widely=
 recognized scientific images of all time.=C2=A0
This outsized level of recognition is warranted. Since the publication of t=
he double helix in 1953, biology has been irreversibly transformed. With th=
e structure of DNA solved, a domino cascade of foundational discoveries fol=
lowed. The timeline of these rapid discoveries reveals a deep truth about l=
iving systems: structure is inextricably linked to function.=C2=A0
The fact that DNA is a double helix with two separable strands gave direct =
clues into how information was replicated between cells in the body, and ul=
timately between parents and their offspring. By 1957, Francis Crick presen=
ted on the central dogma of molecular biology, which describes the flow of =
information from DNA to RNA to proteins. Only a year later, scientists empi=
rically demonstrated the mechanism of DNA replication.
By the middle of the 1960=E2=80=99s, the genetic code=E2=80=94how heritable=
 information is actually stored in DNA=E2=80=94was cracked. It took slightl=
y longer than a decade for the discovery of the double helix to completely =
change our understanding of biology.=C2=A0
The double helix is considered to be the starting point for the field of st=
ructural biology. The speed at which massive problems in genetics were solv=
ed based on the double helix caused a ripple effect throughout the life sci=
ences. It became possible to work at the atomic scale. Atomic structures of=
 molecules and proteins inside of cells gave scientists valuable clues abou=
t their function.
The molecular biology revolution has transformed our view of living systems=
=2E Diseases are no longer viewed as unex=
plainable mysteries, but as molecula=
r programs gone awry. If crops underperform, farmers reach to genetically m=
odified organisms as their primary solution. Answers about ancestry and hea=
lth risks are waiting to be read out from our DNA by consumer offerings. Th=
e entire biotechnology sector=E2=80=94which now produces [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/0532ca50-e23d-453f-a6f1-f=
0369bcee088?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] north of $500 billion in annua=
l revenue in the U.S. alone=E2=80=94is a result of this paradigm shift.
The pharmaceutical industry=E2=80=94which has incumbents that have been aro=
und for centuries [ https://substack.com/redirect/89814069-602a-435f-a54d-9=
0d5706e7803?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ]=E2=80=94required disruption to adapt to the new molecular world order=
=2E One of the most iconic stories of thi=
s era is the journey that Joshua Bog=
er took to form Vertex Pharmaceuticals, which Barry Werth chronicled in The=
 Billion-Dollar Molecule [ https://substack.com/redirect/1705549d-ccc1-4c2e=
-95f8-2350dc8a4893?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ].
With an impressive background as a chemist, Joshua Boger started his career=
 as a scientist at Merck & Co. in 1978. From the very outset, Boger arrived=
 at Merck with an iconoclastic attitude and a unique view of how drug disco=
very should work. At the time, drug makers were primarily focused on making=
 new molecules=E2=80=94the structure of the drug targets that molecules act=
ually bound to was a secondary consideration. Boger thought in reverse.=C2=
=A0
He was fascinated by the power of structural biology, and wanted to use kno=
wledge of the structure of drug targets to guide the design process of new =
therapies. If knowing the molecular structure of DNA transformed genetics, =
shouldn=E2=80=99t the same revolution be possible within drug discovery?
In his very first project at Merck, Boger used information from X-ray struc=
tures of enzymes to design a renin inhibitor [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/1627d196-19e1-4f92-affe-7ad9a3bd801b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that was 1,000 times more potent than Merc=
k=E2=80=99s existing drug. An analogy here is that drug discovery is like f=
inding a key (drug) that fits into a lock (drug target). Boger was intensel=
y focused on using the structure of the lock to accelerate this process.
Boger left Merck to found Vertex Pharmaceuticals in 1989. The goal of Verte=
x was to place rational drug design=E2=80=94the intensive computer modeling=
 of target structures and the chemical binding of drugs=E2=80=94at the cent=
er of the drug discovery process. This transition was a major success. Both=
 Vertex and the broader rational design thesis have had a substantial impac=
t on the drug discovery industry. By leveraging structural biology, Vertex =
developed the first drug to treat the underlying genetic cause of cystic fi=
brosis. Vertex has been one of the top performing stocks in the S&P 500=E2=
=80=94it has compounded at 14.3% since its 1993 IPO=E2=80=94and its influen=
ce has been felt far beyond Wall Street. Effectively all major pharma compa=
nies have worked hard to expand their efforts in structure-based drug desig=
n.
The broad success of structural biology as a discipline extends beyond the =
double helix and the advent of rational drug design. Over the years, many t=
echnologies rapidly improved. It became easier to produce proteins, crystal=
lize them, and solve their structures. X-ray based techniques became much e=
asier and more accurate, and computers got much faster. Entirely new techno=
logies like electron cryogenic electron microscopy [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/b2f083e6-7936-4580-abbf-01c022a31ae2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] came on the scene. As researchers so=
lved more and more structures, they poured them into the Worldwide Protein =
Data Bank (PBD) [ https://substack.com/redirect/dfa94be7-72d7-43a0-86a1-df6=
5ba2aa8b2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ].
As the PDB grew, scientists began to wonder if it would be possible to solv=
e the longstanding problem of protein structure prediction. Would it be pos=
sible to learn the rules of biophysics that dictate the shape that a linear=
 string of amino acids=E2=80=94the building blocks of proteins=E2=80=94will=
 fold into?
Even with improvements to measurement tools, experimentally solving protein=
 structures is more of an art than a science. Countless hours of expert wor=
k are still spent tweaking and refining models. Being able to computational=
ly predict accurate protein structures could accelerate structural biology =
and take the field to another level. Every two years, scientists participat=
ed in the Critical Assessment of protein Structure Prediction (CASP) challe=
nge to benchmark progress on this problem.
The field steadily marched forward over the years, until DeepMind [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/0086fe83-d07b-44e2-ada3-b54acec2e8a3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] made an entry and thi=
ngs started to get really interesting really fast.
Chapter 2: AI=E2=80=99s Bio Breakthrough
AI is starting to produce truly magical [ https://substack.com/redirect/a32=
9a40a-76bb-43b4-87ab-37cf272dbca3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] results=E2=80=94whether in the world of images,=
